{
  "The risk-return tradeoff means:": "",
  "Risk and return are unrelated": "",
  "Low-risk investments earn the highest returns": "",
  "Higher potential returns require accepting higher risk": "",
  "Higher risk always results in losing money": "",
  "The risk-return tradeoff is a fundamental investing principle: to pursue higher potential gains, investors must accept greater uncertainty and the possibility of larger losses.": "",
  "Which investment has the lowest risk?": "",
  "Small-cap growth stocks": "",
  "Cryptocurrency": "",
  "US Treasury bills": "",
  "Individual tech stocks": "",
  "US Treasury bills are backed by the full faith and credit of the US government and are considered essentially risk-free. They offer the lowest returns but virtually eliminate default risk.": "",
  "Standard deviation in investing measures:": "",
  "The average return of an investment": "",
  "How much returns vary from their average (higher SD = more unpredictable)": "",
  "The minimum possible return": "",
  "The maximum possible return": "",
  "Standard deviation quantifies volatility by measuring how widely returns disperse around the mean. A stock with 20% SD is twice as volatile as one with 10% SD, meaning outcomes are much less predictable.": "",
  "A stock with a beta of 1.5 is:": "",
  "Exactly as volatile as the market": "",
  "Less volatile than the overall market": "",
  "50% more volatile than the market": "",
  "Risk-free": "",
  "Beta measures sensitivity to market movements. A beta of 1.5 means the stock tends to move 1.5x the market: if the market drops 10%, this stock may drop 15%. Conversely, market gains are also amplified.": "",
  "Diversification reduces risk by:": "",
  "Avoiding the stock market entirely": "",
  "Concentrating in one top-performing stock": "",
  "Spreading investments so poor performance in one is offset by better performance in others": "",
  "Eliminating all possible risk": "",
  "Diversification mixes investments with different return patterns. When one holding drops, others may hold steady or rise, smoothing overall portfolio returns and reducing the impact of any single loss.": "",
  "Systematic risk (market risk) is:": "",
  "Easily eliminated through diversification": "",
  "Risk affecting the entire market that cannot be diversified away": "",
  "Always avoidable": "",
  "Risk specific to a single company": "",
  "Systematic risk includes recessions, inflation, wars, and pandemics that affect all investments simultaneously. No amount of diversification eliminates it; only reducing market exposure (e.g., holding more bonds or cash) mitigates it.": "",
  "A 25-year-old saving for retirement can tolerate _____ risk than a 60-year-old retiring soon.": "",
  "The same, despite what intuition might initially": "",
  "No risk at all, which is a common assumption": "",
  "More (with more time to recover from market downturns)": "",
  "Less, despite what intuition might initially": "",
  "With a 40-year horizon, a young investor has decades to recover from bear markets. A near-retiree cannot afford a 50% portfolio drop with only 5 years to recovery, so they need more conservative allocations.": "",
  "Asset allocation accounts for approximately _____ of portfolio performance variation.": "",
  "~90%": "",
  "10%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "25%": "",
  "Research by Brinson, Hood, and Beebower found that asset allocation explains roughly 90% of variation in portfolio returns. Individual stock selection and market timing have far less impact than the overall mix of stocks, bonds, and cash.": "",
  "The Sharpe ratio measures:": "",
  "Total return of an investment": "",
  "Risk-adjusted return: excess return per unit of risk (higher is better)": "",
  "Only the risk level of a portfolio": "",
  "Only the fees charged by a fund": "",
  "Sharpe ratio = (Portfolio Return - Risk-Free Rate) / Standard Deviation. It tells you how much excess return you earn for each unit of risk taken. A Sharpe ratio of 1.0 or above is generally considered good.": "",
  "Inflation risk means:": "",
  "Investment returns may not keep pace with rising prices, reducing purchasing power": "",
  "Only cash holdings are affected by inflation": "",
  "Prices are decreasing over time": "",
  "There is no impact of inflation on investments": "",
  "If inflation is 3% and your investment earns 2%, your real return is -1%. Your money buys less over time even though the nominal value increased. This is why stocks, which historically outpace inflation, are important for long-term portfolios.": "",
  "What is 'unsystematic risk' (specific risk)?": "",
  "Risk that can never be reduced or eliminated": "",
  "Risk caused by changes in interest rates": "",
  "Risk that affects the entire market equally": "",
  "Risk specific to a company or industry that can be reduced through diversification": "",
  "Unsystematic risk includes events like a CEO scandal, product recall, or industry downturn. Owning 20-30 stocks across different sectors largely eliminates this risk, which is why diversification is so powerful.": "",
  "What does 'beta' measure in finance?": "",
  "The total annual return of a stock": "",
  "A stock's volatility relative to the overall market (beta of 1 = same volatility as the market)": "",
  "The price-to-earnings ratio of a stock": "",
  "The dividend yield of a stock": "",
  "Beta measures how much a stock moves relative to the market. Beta > 1 means more volatile than the market; beta < 1 means less volatile. A beta of 0.5 means the stock typically moves half as much as the market.": "",
  "What is 'risk tolerance'?": "",
  "An investor's ability and willingness to endure declines in portfolio value in pursuit of higher returns": "",
  "The maximum amount of money you can invest": "",
  "The risk level of the stock market at any given time": "",
  "The interest rate on government bonds": "",
  "Risk tolerance is shaped by age, time horizon, financial goals, income stability, and personal temperament. It determines how aggressively or conservatively your portfolio should be allocated.": "",
  "What does 'liquidity risk' mean?": "",
  "The risk of being unable to sell an investment quickly without a significant loss in value": "",
  "The risk of investing in companies that produce liquids": "",
  "The risk of a bank running out of cash for withdrawals": "",
  "The risk of having too much cash in a portfolio": "",
  "Liquidity risk means you may not be able to sell an asset quickly at a fair price. Real estate and private equity have high liquidity risk; stocks traded on major exchanges have low liquidity risk.": "",
  "What does the 'efficient frontier' represent?": "",
  "The safest portfolio available with zero risk": "",
  "The set of portfolios offering the highest expected return for each level of risk": "",
  "A portfolio consisting only of government bonds": "",
  "The maximum amount an investor can contribute to retirement accounts": "",
  "The efficient frontier is a curve showing optimal portfolios. Portfolios on the frontier maximize return for each risk level. Portfolios below the frontier are sub-optimal because they could achieve higher return at the same risk.": "",
  "What does 'Modern Portfolio Theory' (MPT) suggest?": "",
  "Combining assets with different correlations reduces overall portfolio risk without necessarily reducing expected return": "",
  "Investors should own only one stock to maximize focus": "",
  "All bonds are safer than all stocks in every situation": "",
  "Investors should avoid all risky assets": "",
  "MPT, developed by Harry Markowitz, shows that portfolio risk depends on the correlations between assets, not just their individual risks. Mixing assets that do not move in lockstep can reduce risk while maintaining returns.": "",
  "What does 'volatility' mean in investing?": "",
  "The liquidity of an investment": "",
  "The total return of an investment over time": "",
  "The degree to which an investment's price fluctuates over time, measured by standard deviation": "",
  "The amount of money invested in a portfolio": "",
  "Volatility measures the magnitude and frequency of price swings. High volatility means prices change dramatically (both up and down); low volatility means more stable, predictable prices.": "",
  "What is 'correlation' in portfolio management?": "",
  "The total return of two investments added together": "",
  "The fee charged for holding multiple investments": "",
  "The number of investments in a portfolio": "",
  "A statistical measure (-1 to +1) of how two investments move relative to each other": "",
  "Correlation of +1 means perfect co-movement (no diversification benefit), -1 means perfect opposite movement (maximum diversification), and 0 means no relationship. Lower correlations between portfolio holdings reduce overall risk.": "",
  "What does 'risk-adjusted return' mean?": "",
  "The total return after subtracting inflation": "",
  "A return metric that accounts for the amount of risk taken; it evaluates how efficiently an investment generates returns per unit of risk": "",
  "The return after subtracting all fees and taxes": "",
  "The maximum return possible from a risk-free investment": "",
  "Risk-adjusted return helps compare investments with different risk levels. A 10% return with 25% standard deviation may be less attractive than an 8% return with 10% standard deviation — the Sharpe ratio captures this.": "",
  "What does 'time horizon' mean in investing?": "",
  "The length of time an investor expects to hold investments before needing the money": "",
  "The time zone in which the stock exchange operates": "",
  "The expiration date on an investment product": "",
  "The hours of the day when markets are open for trading": "",
  "Time horizon is one of the most important factors in choosing investments. Longer horizons allow for riskier allocations since there is more time to recover from market downturns.": "",
  "Investment A has returns of 8%, 12%, 6%, 14% over four years. Investment B has returns of 9%, 10%, 9.5%, 10.5%. Both average 10%, but which carries more risk and why?": "",
  "Investment A has more risk because its returns vary more widely (higher standard deviation)": "",
  "Investment B because its returns are closer together": "",
  "Neither has any risk since both produced positive returns": "",
  "Both have identical risk since the average return is the same": "",
  "Investment A's returns range from 6% to 14% (spread of 8 points) while B's range from 9% to 10.5% (spread of 1.5 points). A's higher standard deviation means greater uncertainty about future outcomes, even with the same average.": "",
  "Portfolio X earns 12% with a standard deviation of 15%. Portfolio Y earns 10% with a standard deviation of 8%. If the risk-free rate is 3%, which has a better Sharpe ratio?": "",
  "Portfolio Y (Sharpe = 0.875) — better risk-adjusted return": "",
  "They have equal Sharpe ratios": "",
  "Cannot be determined without more information": "",
  "Portfolio X (Sharpe = 0.60)": "",
  "X: (12% - 3%) / 15% = 0.60. Y: (10% - 3%) / 8% = 0.875. Portfolio Y earns more return per unit of risk, making it the more efficient investment despite having a lower total return.": "",
  "A savings account earns 2% while inflation is 3.5%. An investor keeps $50,000 in the account for 10 years. What happens to the purchasing power?": "",
  "Purchasing power stays the same": "",
  "Purchasing power declines because the real return is -1.5% per year, losing roughly $7,000 in buying power over 10 years": "",
  "The account is fully protected from inflation by FDIC insurance": "",
  "Purchasing power increases because the balance grows": "",
  "Real return = 2% - 3.5% = -1.5% per year. Over 10 years, the purchasing power drops by roughly 14%: $50,000 x (1 - 0.015)^10 ≈ $42,900 in today's dollars, even though the nominal balance grew to ~$61,000.": "",
  "During the 2008 financial crisis, the S&P 500 dropped approximately 50%. An investor with $200,000 who panic-sold at the bottom and waited until the market fully recovered in 2013 to reinvest missed approximately how much in recovery gains?": "",
  "They saved $100,000 by avoiding further losses": "",
  "They made money by selling and buying back later": "",
  "They lost nothing since they sold before it got worse": "",
  "They locked in $100,000 in losses and missed the ~100% recovery, leaving them with $100,000 while a patient investor recovered to $200,000+": "",
  "The panic seller sold $200K worth of stocks at the bottom for $100K. By 2013, the market had fully recovered. The patient investor's $200K was restored, but the panic seller only had $100K in cash. Selling low and buying high is the worst outcome.": "",
